<h2>Solar Panels in Idaho</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Idaho's solar irradiance levels range from 4.5 to 5.5 peak sun hours daily depending on location, with southern Idaho receiving the highest solar radiation. The state benefits from over 200 sunny days per year, with summer months providing peak production from May through September. Boise and the Treasure Valley receive approximately 5.2 peak sun hours daily, while northern regions like Coeur d'Alene average around 4.6 hours. These levels are comparable to solar-friendly states like Colorado and significantly higher than many East Coast locations.</p>

<p>Seasonal variations in Idaho create interesting production patterns, with summer months generating 40-50% more electricity than winter months. However, the state's cold, clear winter days often provide excellent solar conditions, and snow reflection can actually boost panel performance. A typical 6kW residential solar system in Idaho produces between 7,500-9,000 kWh annually, easily covering the average Idaho home's electricity consumption of 12,000-13,000 kWh when properly sized.</p>

<p>Idaho's high elevation and dry climate provide ideal conditions for solar panel efficiency. The cooler temperatures at higher elevations actually improve panel performance, as photovoltaic cells operate more efficiently in moderate temperatures. Combined with minimal air pollution and low humidity, Idaho's environmental conditions help solar panels maintain peak performance throughout their 25-30 year lifespan.</p>

