<h2>HVAC Systems in Idaho</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Idaho's continental climate creates significant heating and cooling demands, with winter temperatures often dropping below freezing and summer temperatures reaching 90-100¬∞F in many areas. Heating typically represents 40-60% of annual energy usage, while cooling accounts for 15-25%, making efficient systems crucial for energy savings. The state's low humidity levels mean evaporative cooling can be effective in some regions, while heat pumps are increasingly popular for their dual heating and cooling efficiency.</p>

<p>For cooling systems, SEER ratings of 16-18 are recommended for most Idaho locations, balancing efficiency with cost-effectiveness. In northern Idaho's cooler climate, SEER 14-16 systems may be sufficient, while southern regions benefit from higher efficiency units. For heating, HSPF ratings of 9.0 or higher are recommended for heat pumps, while gas furnaces should have AFUE ratings of 90% or higher to maximize efficiency during Idaho's cold winters.</p>

<p>Dual-fuel systems combining heat pumps with gas furnace backup are particularly effective in Idaho, using the heat pump for moderate temperatures and switching to gas when outdoor temperatures drop below 25-30¬∞F. This approach maximizes efficiency across Idaho's wide temperature range while ensuring reliable heating during extreme cold snaps that can last several days or weeks.</p>

