<h2>Idaho Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Idaho offers several attractive incentives for solar and HVAC installations, making these investments highly cost-effective for homeowners. The primary incentives include:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Tax Credit (30%):</strong> The federal government provides a 30% tax credit for solar panel installations through 2032, then decreasing to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and permitting. For a \$20,000 solar system, homeowners receive a \$6,000 tax credit, directly reducing their federal tax liability.</li>

<li><strong>Idaho Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Idaho exempts solar energy systems from property tax assessments, meaning the added value from solar panels won't increase property taxes. This exemption applies to both residential and commercial installations and continues for the life of the system, providing ongoing savings.</li>

<li><strong>Idaho Power Net Metering:</strong> Idaho Power customers with solar systems up to 25kW can participate in net metering, receiving retail rate credits for excess electricity sent to the grid. These credits roll over month-to-month and are paid out annually at avoided cost rates if unused.</li>

<li><strong>Idaho Power Energy Efficiency Programs:</strong> Idaho Power offers rebates up to \$1,000 for high-efficiency heat pumps, \$500 for programmable thermostats, and various other HVAC efficiency upgrades. The utility also provides energy audits and financing options for qualified improvements.</li>

<li><strong>USDA Rural Development Grants:</strong> Rural Idaho properties may qualify for USDA grants covering up to 25% of renewable energy system costs, combined with low-interest loans. This program can be stacked with other incentives for maximum savings.</li>
</ul>

<p>To maximize incentives, homeowners should work with certified installers familiar with local programs and ensure all documentation is properly submitted. The combination of federal, state, and utility incentives can reduce total system costs by 40-50%, significantly improving payback periods and long-term returns.</p>

